===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*peh‚ÇÇw-}}
From {{bor|en|NL.|encyclopaedia|t=general education}}, from Renaissance {{der|en|grc|·ºêŒ≥Œ∫œÖŒ∫ŒªŒøœÄŒ±ŒπŒ¥ŒµŒØŒ±|t=education in the circle of arts and sciences}}, a mistaken [[univerbation|univerbated]] form of {{der|en|grc-koi|·ºêŒ≥Œ∫œçŒ∫ŒªŒπŒøœÇ œÄŒ±ŒπŒ¥ŒµŒØ·æ±|t=education in the circle of arts and sciences}}, from {{m|grc|·ºêŒ≥Œ∫œçŒ∫ŒªŒπŒøœÇ|t=circular}} + {{m|grc|œÄŒ±ŒπŒ¥ŒµŒØ·æ±|t=child-rearing, education}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|Canada}} {{IPA|en|/…ônÀås…ô…™.kl…ôÀàpi.di.…ô/}}
* {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA|en|/…™nÀåsa…™.kl…ôÀàpi(Àê).di.…ô/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-encyclopedia.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|iÀêdi…ô}}
* {{hyphenation|en|en|cy|clo|pe|dia}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|encyclopediae|encyclopedi√¶}}

# A [[comprehensive]] [[reference work]] (often spanning several printed volumes) with articles (usually arranged in alphabetical order, or sometimes arranged by category) on a range of [[subjects]], sometimes general, sometimes limited to a particular field.
#: {{ux|en|I only use the library for the '''encyclopedia''', as we‚Äôve got most other books here.}}
#: {{ux|en|His life's work was a four-volume '''encyclopedia''' of aviation topics.}}
# {{lb|en|dated}} The [[circle]] of [[arts]] and [[sciences]]; a [[comprehensive]] summary of [[knowledge]], or of a branch of knowledge.

====Usage notes====
The spelling ''encyclopedia'' is standard in American English, preferred in Canadian English, accepted in Australian and International English, and also very common in British English. It is more common than ''encyclopaedia'', for example, in UK newspapers on Google News in 2009 by a 7:3 margin.

