==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/pa änd/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-pound.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|a änd}}

===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*(s)pend-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|pound}}, from {{inh|en|ang|pund||a pound, weight}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*pundƒÖ||pound, weight}}, an early borrowing from {{der|en|la|pond≈ç||by weight}}, ablative form of {{m|la|pondus||weight}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*pend-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*spend-||to pull, stretch}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|pond}}, {{cog|de|Pfund}}, {{cog|sv|pund}}. {{doublet|en|pood}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}} (sometimes '''pound''' after numerals)

# A [[unit]] of [[mass]] equal to 16 [[avoirdupois]] ounces (= 453.592 37 g). Today this value is the most common meaning of "pound" as a unit of weight.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=28 July 2010|author=Rachel Williams|work=The Guardian|title=Mothers who lose weight before further pregnancy ‚Äòreduce risks‚Äô|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2010/jul/28/mothers-lose-weight-reduce-risks?INTCMP=SRCH|passage=Research shows that retaining even one or two '''pounds''' after giving birth can make problems more likely in a subsequent pregnancy, experts said, with women who have several children facing a "slippery slope" if they continue to gain weight each time.}}
#: {{syn|en|lb}}
# A unit of [[mass]] equal to 12 [[troy weight|troy ounce]]s (‚âà 373.242 g). Today, this is a common unit of weight when measuring precious metals, and is little used elsewhere.
#: {{syn|en|lb t}}
# {{lb|en|US}} The symbol {{unsupported|#}} ([[octothorpe]], [[hash]]) <!--isn't this "pound sign" rather than "pound"?-->
#: {{syn|en|hash|sharp}}
# The unit of currency used in the United Kingdom and its [[dependency|dependencies]]. It is divided into 100 [[pence]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=November 11 2012|author=Carole Cadwalladr|work=Observer|title=Do online courses spell the end for the traditional university?|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/2012/nov/11/online-free-learning-end-of-university?INTCMP=SRCH|passage=For students in developing countries who can't get it any other way, or for students in the first world, who can but may choose not to. Pay thousands of '''pounds''' a year for your education? Or get it free online?}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1860|author={{w|George Eliot}}|title=The Mill on the Floss|volume_plain=book 5|chapter=6|passage="Only a hundred and ninety-three '''pound'''," said Mr. Tulliver. "You've brought less o' late; but young fellows like to have their own way with their money. Though I didn't do as I liked before I was of age." He spoke with rather timid discontent.}}
#: {{syn|en|¬£|pound sterling|GBP|quid|nicker}}
# Any of various units of [[currency]] used in Egypt and Lebanon, and formerly in the Republic of Ireland, Cyprus and Israel.
#* {{RQ:Joyce Ulysses|chapter=[Episode 4]|passage=He glanced back through what he had read and, while feeling his water flow quietly, he envied kindly Mr Beaufoy who had written it and received payment of three '''pounds''', thirteen and six.}}
#: {{syn|en|punt}}
# Any of various units of [[currency]] formerly used in the [[United States]].
#: {{ux|en|the Rhode Island '''pound'''; the New Hampshire '''pound'''}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010|author=Steven Field|title=Dusty's Fort|publisher=|url=|isbn=1445292416|page=33|passage=He knocked out cans of warm cola at two '''pound''' fifty a time.}}
# Abbreviation for [[pound-force]], a unit of force/weight. Using this abbreviation to describe pound-force is inaccurate and unscientific.

=====Usage notes=====
* Internationally, the "pound" has most commonly referred to the UK pound, ¬£, (pound sterling). The other currencies were usually distinguished in some way, e.g., the "Irish pound" or the "punt".
* In the vicinity of each other country calling its currency the pound among English speakers the local currency would be the "pound", with all others distinguished, e.g., the "British pound", the "Egyptian pound" etc.
* The general plural of "pound" has usually been "pounds" (at least since Chaucer), but the continuing use of the Old English genitive or neuter "pound" as the plural after numerals (for both currency and weight) is common in some regions. It can be considered correct, or colloquial, depending on region.

