#*: When I short haue shorne my sowce face<br>& swigg‚Äôd my horny barrell,<br>In an oaken Inne I '''pound''' my skin<br>as a suite of guilt apparrell
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1644|author={{w|John Milton}}|title={{w|Areopagitica}}; A speech of Mr. John Milton for the Liberty of Unlicenc‚Äôd Printing, to the Parlament of England|passage=And he who were pleasantly disposed, could not well avoid to liken it to the exploit of that gallant man, who thought to '''pound''' up the crows by shutting his park gate.}}

===Etymology 3===
From an alteration of earlier {{m|en|poun}}, {{m|en|pown}}, from {{inh|en|enm|pounen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|p≈´nian||to pound, beat, bray, bruise, crush}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*p≈´n≈çnƒÖ||to break to pieces, pulverise}}. Related to {{cog|stq|P√ºn||debris, fragments}}, {{cog|nl|puin||debris, fragments, rubbish}}, {{cog|nds|pun||fragments}}. Perhaps influenced by '''Etymology 2''' {{cog|enm|*pound}}, {{m|enm|pond}}, from {{cog|ang|*pund}}, {{m|ang|pynd}}, in relation to the hollow [[mortar]] for pounding with the [[pestle]].

====Alternative forms====
* {{l|en|poun}}, {{l|en|pown}} {{qualifier|obsolete or dialectal}}

