===Etymology 2===
{{inh|en|enm|crowen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|crƒÅwan}} (past tense {{m|ang|crƒìow}}, past participle {{m|ang|crƒÅwen}}), from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*krƒìanƒÖ}}, from {{onomatopoeic|en|title=imitative}} {{der|en|ine-pro|*gerH-||to cry hoarsely}}.<ref>{{R:American_Heritage_Dictionary|crow}}</ref>

Compare {{cog|nl|kraaien}}, {{cog|de|kr√§hen}}, {{cog|lt|gr√≥ti}}, {{cog|ru|–≥—Ä–∞ÃÅ—è—Ç—å}}). Related to {{m|en|croak}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|past2=crew|past2_qual=UK|past_ptc2=crown|past_ptc2_qual=archaic}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[make#Verb|make]] the [[shrill#Adjective|shrill]] [[sound#Noun|sound]] characteristic of a [[rooster]]; to make a sound in this manner, either in [[gaiety]], [[joy]], [[pleasure#Noun|pleasure]], or [[defiance]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Hamlet Q1-2|act=I|scene=ii|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jrU8AAAAYAAJ&pg=PT14|passage=Yet once me thought it [the ghost of [[w:Prince Hamlet|Hamlet]]'s father] was about to ≈øpeake, / And lifted vp his head to motion, / Like as he would ≈øpeake, but euen the / The morning cocke '''crew''' lowd, and in all ha≈øte / It ≈øhrunke in ha≈øte away, and vani≈øhed / Our ≈øight.}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1784|title=The House that Jack Built|page=8|text=This is the Cock that '''crowed''' in the Morn[.]}}
#* {{RQ:Tennyson Princess|part=II|page=37|passage='You are that Psyche' Cyril said again / 'The mother of the sweetest little maid, / That ever '''crow'd''' for kisses.'}}
#* {{RQ:Trollope He Knew|volume=I|chapter=Lady Milborough as Ambassador|page=87|quote=The child was at this time about ten months old, and was a strong, hearty, happy infant, always laughing when he was awake and always sleeping when he did not laugh, because his little limbs were free from pain and his little stomach was not annoyed by internal troubles. He kicked, and '''crowed''', and sputtered, when his mother took him, and put up his little fingers to clutch her hair, and was to her as a young god upon the earth. Nothing in the world had ever been created so beautiful, so joyous, so satisfactory, so divine!}}
#* {{RQ:Lawrence Sons and Lovers|chapter=III|page=48|passage=Hearing the miner's footsteps, the baby would put up his arms and '''crow'''.}}
#* {{quote-song|en|author={{w|Bob Dylan}}|title=[[w:Don't Think Twice, It's All Right|Don‚Äôt Think Twice, It‚Äôs All Right]]|album=[[w:The Freewheelin' Bob Dylan|The Freewheelin‚Äô Bob Dylan]]|year=1962|passage=When your rooster '''crows''' at the break o' dawn / Look out your window and I'll be gone.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[shout#Verb|shout]] in [[exultation]] or [[defiance]]; to [[brag#Verb|brag]].
#: {{ux|en|He‚Äôs been '''crowing''' all day about winning the game of cards.}}
#* {{quote-web|en|author=Julianne Tveten|title=Zucktown, USA|url=https://thebaffler.com/latest/zucktown-usa-tveten|work=The Baffler|date=27 September 2017|passage=Touting its sponsorship of local engineering and sustainability programs, Amazon '''crows''' about such ‚Äúinvestments‚Äù as its dog park, playing fields, art installations, and Buckyball-reminiscent domical gardens.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|music}} To [[test#Verb|test]] the [[reed]] of a [[double reed]] [[instrument]] by [[place#Verb|placing]] the reed alone in the [[mouth#Noun|mouth]] and [[blow#Verb|blowing]] it.

=====Usage notes=====
The past tense {{m|en|crew}} in modern usage is confined to literary and metaphorical uses, usually with reference to the story of Peter in ''Luke 22.60''. The past participle {{m|en|crown}} is similarly poetical.

