===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To become brown.
#: {{ux|en|Fry the onions until they '''brown'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title={{w|The Omnivore's Dilemma}}|author={{w|Michael Pollan}}|publisher=The Penguin Press|year=2006|ISBN=1594200823|passage=The chicken was '''browning''' nicely, the skin beginning to crisp and take on the toasty tones of oiled wood.|page=269}}
# {{lb|en|cooking|transitive}} To cook something until it becomes brown.
#: {{ux|en|'''Brown''' the onions in a large frying pan.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|transitive}} To [[tan]].
#: {{ux|en|Light-skinned people tend to '''brown''' when exposed to the sun.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To make brown or dusky.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1807|author=Joel Barlow|title={{w|The Columbiad}}|passage=A trembling twilight o'er the welkin moves, / '''Browns''' the dim void and darkens deep the groves.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give a bright brown colour to, as to gun barrels, by forming a thin [[coating]] of [[oxide]] on their surface.
#* {{quote-book|en|1860|Andrew Ure|title=Ure‚Äôs Dictionary of Arts, Manufactures, and Mines|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Obl3pV1XWXUC&pg=PA463|page=463|passage=It is mixed uniformly with olive oil, and rubbed upon the iron slightly heated, which is afterwards exposed to the air, till the wished-for degree of '''browning''' is produced.}}
# {{lb|en|demography|transitive|intransitive|slang|ethnic slur|usually|derogatory|offensive}} To turn progressively more [[Middle Eastern]], [[Hispanic]] or [[Latino]], in the context of the population of a geographic region.
#: {{ux|en|the '''browning''' of America}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To treat with deference, or respect.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1961|chapter=Chapter Eleven: The White House|genre=fiction|first=Arthur |last=Hailey|title=In High Places|format=e-book, hardcover, paperback|passage=James Howden dropped into an upholstered wing chair. ‚ÄúThey certainly did us '''brown''' last night,‚Äù he remarked. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôd think if they are making a switch, being considerate and so on, they‚Äôd be a bit more subtle.‚Äù}}

