* {{sense|Roman month}} {{l|en|Februarius}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|Februarie}}, {{m|enm|februari}}, {{m|enm|februare}}, from {{der|en|la|FebruƒÅrius||the [[month]] of the [[Februa]]}}, from {{m|la|Fƒìbrua||the [[purging|Purging]]s, the [[purification|Purification]]s}}, a Roman holiday two days after its [[ides]] (i.e., Feb. 15), + {{m|la|-arius||[[-ary]]: ''[[form]]ing [[adjective]]s''}}. {{m|la|Fƒìbrua}} from {{m|la|fƒìbruum||[[purging]]}}, from an earlier {{der|en|sbv}} word, possibly from {{der|en|ine-pro|*d ∞ewh‚ÇÇ-||[[smoke]], [[haze]]}} and thus cognate with {{m|en|thio-||[[sulfurous]]}} and {{der|en|grc|Œ∏Œµ·øñŒøŒΩ||[[sulfur]]}} or from {{der|en|ine-pro|*d ∞eg ∑ ∞ris}}, an extension of the root {{m|ine-pro|*d ∞eg ∑ ∞-|gloss=to [[burn]]}} and thus cognate with {{m|en|fever}} and {{m|la|febris}}. A relatinization abandoning {{der|en|enm|feoverel}}, from {{der|en|fro|feverier}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/Ààf…õb.…π ä.…ô.…πi/|/Ààf…õb.j( ä.)…ô.…πi/|/Ààf…õb.…π…ô.…πi/|/Ààf…õb.…πi/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/Ààf…õb.…πuÀå…õ…πi/|/Ààf…õb.juÀå…õ(…ô)…πi/}}; {{enPR|fƒïb πroÕûo-ƒïr'-ƒì|fƒïb πyoÕûo-ƒïr'-ƒì}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-February.ogg|Audio (GA)}}
* {{audio|en|en-uk-february.ogg|Audio (RP)}}
* {{hyphenation|en|Feb|ru|ary}}<ref>{{R:Hyphenation exception log}}</ref>

The pronunciation of the first ''r'' as {{IPAchar|/j/}} has come about by [[dissimilation]] and [[analogy]] with {{m|en|January}}. In the UK pronunciation {{IPAchar|/Ààf…õb.…πi/}} ({{m|en||*Febry}}) the sequence {{IPAchar|/…π…ô.…πi/}} in {{IPAchar|/Ààf…õb.…π…ô.…πi/}} ({{m|en||*Febrery}}) is simplified to {{IPAchar|/…πi/}} by [[haplology]].

===Proper noun===
{{en-proper noun|Februaries|Februarys}}

# The [[short]] [[month]] following [[January]] and preceding [[March]] in the [[Roman]], [[Julian]], and [[Gregorian calendar]]s, [[use]]d in [[all]] [[three]] [[calendar]]s for [[intercalation]] or [[addition]] of [[leap day]]s.
#* '''2011''', Robert A. Kaster trans. [[w:Macrobius|Macrobius]], ''Saturnalia'', Book I, Chapter xiii, Sections 3‚Äì5:
#*: ...The second he [''[[sc.]]'' [[w:Numa Pompilius|King Numa]]] dedicated to the god [[Februus]], who is believed to control rites of purification: the community had to be purified in that month, when he determined that the Good Gods be paid the offerings due them... Numa soon added one day to January, paying honor to the mystery of the odd number that nature revealed even before [[w:Pythagoras|Pythagoras]]: as a result, both the year as a whole and the individual months (save '''February''') had an odd number of days. (If all twelve months had either an odd or even number of days, their total would be an even number...)
#* '''2011''', Robert A. Kaster trans. [[w:Macrobius|Macrobius]], ''Saturnalia'', Book I, Chapter xiii, Sections 14‚Äì15:
#*: '''February''' was set aside for the intercalation because it was the last month of the year... They departed from the Greeks in one respect, however: whereas the latter intercalated when the final month was over, the Romans intercalated after the twenty-third day of '''February''', at the conclusion of the [[Terminalia]]. They then added on the last five days of '''February''' after the intercalary period, acting on the religious scruple of ancient custom, I think, so that March would follow on '''February''' no matter what.
#* '''2011''', Robert A. Kaster trans. [[w:Macrobius|Macrobius]], ''Saturnalia'', Book I, Chapter xiv, Sections 6‚Äì7:
#*: [[w:Julius Caesar|Julius Caesar]], then, added ten days to the old practice, so that the 365 days in which the sun circles the zodiac would make a year; and to account for the one-quarter day, he ordained that the priests who attended to the months and days would insert one day every fourth year, in the same month and place where the ancients used to intercalate a month, that is, before the last five days of '''February''', and he decreed that it be called the 'twice sixth'... he added no days to '''February''', so that the religious observances offered to the gods of the dead would not be changed...
#: ''Susan was born on '''February''' 29.''
# {{lb|en|rare}} {{given name|en|female|from=English}}.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2011|author=Kristen Ashley|title=For You|passage=‚ÄúCheryl, the man in this photo is a Mr. Dennis Lowe. He worked for a computer software company and he was married. He was impersonating a police officer, a real one by the name of Alexander Colton. He was doing this because he's obsessed with a woman named '''February'''‚Äî‚Äù Nowakowski stopped talking because Cheryl Sheckle's body jerked violently and she let out a muted cry. {{...|‚ÄúFuck, he called her '''February''',‚Äù Sully muttered. ‚ÄúNo,‚Äù Cheryl whispered. [...] ‚ÄúHe said it was a nickname.‚Äù Warren shook his head then,}} ‚ÄúIt isn't a nickname, Cheryl. It's a real person, her name is '''February''' Owens and he's been obsessed with her since they went to high school together.‚Äù}}
