===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|en|enm|marche|t=tract of land along a country's border}}, from {{der|en|fro|marche|t=boundary, frontier}}, from {{der|en|frk|*marku}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*mark≈ç}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*mer«µ-|t=edge, boundary}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|now|_|archaic|historical}} A border region, especially one originally set up to defend a [[boundary]].
#: {{syn|en|frontier|marchland}}
# {{lb|en|historical}} A region at a frontier governed by a [[marquess]].
# Any of various territories with similar meanings or etymologies in their native languages.
#: {{syn|en|county palatinate|county palatine}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1819|author={{w|Lord Byron}}|title={{w|Don Juan (Byron)|Don Juan}}|section=IV|passage=Juan's companion was a Romagnole, / But bred within the '''March''' of old Ancona{{nb...}}.}}

