==English==
{{was wotd|2011|April|24}}
{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
From {{af|en|multicultural|-ism}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/Àåm ålt…™Ààk ålt É…ô…π…ôÀål…™z(…ô)m/}}
* {{audio|en|en-au-multiculturalism.ogg|Audio (AU)}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-multiculturalism.ogg|Audio (Mid-Atlantic)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The characteristics of a society, city etc. which has many different [[ethnic]] or [[national]] cultures mingling freely; political or social policies which support or encourage such [[coexistence]]. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}
#*'''1984''', {{w|David Malouf}}, ''A First Place'', Vintage 2015, p. 18:
#*:The truth is that diversity, a kind of '''multiculturalism''' if we want to call it that, is the norm in any society.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=8 April 1991|author=Barbara Ehrenreich|magazine=Time|passage=Something had to replace the threat of communism, and at last a workable substitute is at hand. "'''Multiculturalism'''," as the new menace is known, has been denounced in the media recently as the new McCarthyism, the new fundamentalism, even the new totalitarianism ‚Äì take your choice.|title=Essay: Teach Diversity ‚Äì with a Smile}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=3 August 2005|author=David Davis MP|work=Daily Telegraph|passage=Britain has pursued a policy of '''multiculturalism''' - allowing people of different cultures to settle without expecting them to integrate into society.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=7 April 2011|title=On a mat and a prayer|magazine=The Economist|passage=Earlier this year he said '''multiculturalism''' had ‚Äúfailed‚Äù, that immigrants needed to ‚Äúmelt‚Äù into French society, and that ‚Äúwe do not want ostentatious prayers in the street in France.‚Äù}}

