==English==
{{wikipedia|dab=thursday (disambiguation)|thursday}}
{{wikipedia|Week-day names}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*d ∞eg ∑ ∞-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|Thursday}}, {{m|enm|Thuresday}}, from {{inh|en|ang|√æursd√¶ƒ°}}, {{m|ang|√æurresd√¶ƒ°||Thursday}}, possibly from a contraction of {{m|ang|√æunresd√¶ƒ°||Thursday|lit=[[Thor]]'s day}}, but more likely of {{der|en|gmq|-}} origin, from {{der|en|non|√æ√≥rsdagr|√æ≈çrsdagr}} or Old {{der|en|da|√æursdag|√æ≈´rsdag|Thursday}}; all from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*√ûunras dag||day of the thunder god}}. Compare {{cog|fy|tongersdei}}, {{cog|nds-de|Dunnersdag}}, {{cog|nl|donderdag}}, {{cog|de|Donnerstag}}, {{cog|da|torsdag}}. More at {{l|en|thunder}}, {{l|en|day}}.

A calque of Latin ''{{l|la|diƒìs Iovis}} ({{l|la|diƒìs Jovis}})'', via an association ({{m|la|interpretƒÅti≈ç germƒÅnica}}) of the god [[Thor]] with the Roman god of thunder [[Jove]] (Jupiter).

