==English==

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*d ∞eg ∑ ∞-|*preyH-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|Friday}}, from {{inh|en|ang|frƒ´ƒ°ed√¶ƒ°}}. Compound of {{m|ang|frƒ´ƒ°e}} and {{m|ang|d√¶ƒ°|t=day}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*Frƒ´jƒÅ dag}}, a calque of {{der|en|la|diƒìs Veneris}}, via an association ({{m|la|interpretƒÅti≈ç germƒÅnica}}) of the goddess [[Frigg]] with the Roman goddess of love [[Venus]].

Compare {{cog|fy|freed}}, {{cog|nds-de|Freedag}}, {{m|nds-de|Friedag}}, {{cog|nl|vrijdag}}, {{cog|de|Freitag}}, {{cog|da|fredag}}.
{{cog|non|Frigg}} (genitive {{m|no|Friggjar}}), {{cog|osx|Fri}}, and {{cog|ang|Frig}} are derived from {{cog|gem-pro|*Frijj≈ç}}. Frigg is cognate with {{cog|sa|‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ø‡§Ø‡§æ|tr=priyƒÅÃÅ|t=wife}}. The root also appears in {{cog|osx|fri|t=beloved lady}}; in {{cog|sv|fria}}, in {{cog|da|-}} and {{cog|no|-}} as {{m|da|fri|t=to propose for marriage}}; a related meaning exists in Icelandic as {{m|is|frj√°|t=to love}} and similarly in {{cog|nl|vrijen|t=to make love (to have sex)}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/Ààf…πa…™de…™/|/Ààf…πa…™di/}}
