# {{lb|en|uncountable}} The [[art]] or [[craft#Noun|craft]] of [[compile|compiling]], [[write|writing]], and [[edit#Verb|editing]] [[dictionary|dictionaries]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Craftsman, Feb. 22 &#91;[[Julian calendar]]&#93;. N¬∫ 451.|editor=Sylvanus Urban [pseudonym; {{w|Edward Cave}}]|magazine=[[w:The Gentleman's Magazine|The Gentleman‚Äôs Magazine, and Historical Chronicle]]|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by}} Edward Cave,{{nb...|at St John‚Äôs Gate.}}|date={{J2G|22 February 1735}}|year_published=February 1735|volume=V|page=85|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=p1U3AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA85|column=1|oclc=192374019|passage=[T]here are ≈øeveral Species of Writing, in which a proper Degree of ''Hebetude'' is ab≈øolutely nece≈ø≈øary, as well as in other profe≈ø≈øions; such as '''''Lexicography''''', ''Index-making'', and the like; [...]}}
#* {{RQ:Johnson Dictionary|chapter=Preface|url=https://archive.org/details/b30451541_0001/page/n14/mode/1up|passage=And ≈øuch is the fate of haple≈øs '''lexicography''', that not only darkne≈øs, but light, impedes and di≈øtre≈ø≈øes it; things may be not only too little, but too much known, to be happily illu≈øtrated.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:John Philpot Curran|[John Philpot] Curran]], defence counsel|chapter=612. Trial of James Weldon for High Treason,{{nb...|before the Court Holden under a Commission of Oyer and Terminer and General Gaol Delivery in and for the County of the City of Dublin, in the Kingdom of Ireland, on Monday December 21st, and Tuesday December 22nd: 36 George III. A.D. 1795.}}|editor={{w|Thomas Jones Howell}}|title=[[w:William Cobbett|Cobbett]]‚Äôs Complete Collection of State Trials and Proceedings for High Treason and Other Crimes and Misdemeanors{{nb...|from the Earliest Period to the Year 1783, with Notes and Other Illustrations: Compiled by T. B. Howell, Esq. F.R.S. F.S.A. and Continued from the Year 1783 to the Present Time: by Thomas Howell Jones, Esq.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by T[homas] C[urson] Hansard, Peterborough-Court, Fleet-Street: for}} [[w:Longman|Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme, and Brown]]; [''et al.'']|date=22 December 1795|year_published=1819|volume=XXVI|column=267|columnurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=K7dCAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA267|oclc=712066713|passage=Let me warn you, therefore, against that fallacious '''lexicography''' which forms new words, that undergoing the examination of political slander or intemperate zeal, are considered as having a known acception.‚ÄîWhat is the word?‚ÄîA word that should be discarded, when it is sought to affix to it another meaning than that which it bears in the cases where it is used.}}
