#* {{quote-book|en|author=Ying Hing Soo|chapter=Book Second|translator=Charles Fried. Neumann [''i.e.'', {{w|Karl Friedrich Neumann}}]|title=History of the Pirates who Infested the China Sea, from 1807 to 1810.{{nb...|Translated from the Chinese Original, with Notes and Illustrations}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for the}} [[w:Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland#Oriental Translation Fund of Great Britain and Ireland|Oriental Translation Fund]],{{nb...|and sold by J[ohn] Murray, Albemarle Street; Parbury, Allen, & Co., Leadenhall Street; Thacker & Co., Calcutta; Treuttel & W√ºrtz, Paris; and E. Fleischer, Leipsig}}|year=1831|section=footnote|page=54|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=8aUCAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA54|oclc=250438210|passage=There exist different forms of this character, but I think we should not presume to make an etymology of a Chinese character without being authorized by the [[w:Shuowen Jiezi|Shw«í w«én]], the oldest and most genuine source of Chinese '''lexicography'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=A[nthony] P[aul] Cowie|chapter=The Role of the Computer in Learner Lexicography|title=English Dictionaries for Foreign Learners: A History|location=Oxford, Oxfordshire|publisher=[[w:Oxford University Press|Clarendon Press]]|year=1999|section=section 4.1 (Introduction)|page=118|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=WRHzbsSjm0YC&pg=PA118|isbn=978-0-19-823506-4|passage=Without doubt, the most important single development in learner '''lexicography''' from the mid-1970s onwards has been the steadily increasing involvement of the computer at all stages of the dictionary-making process, from data gathering and analysis at one end, to compilation, production, and revision at the other.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Amy Chi|chapter=Researching Pedagogical Lexicography|editor=Howard Jackson|title=The Bloomsbury Companion to Lexicography|series=Bloomsbury Companions|location=London; New York, N.Y.|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic, {{w|Bloomsbury Publishing}}|year=2013|page=165|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=09JBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA165|isbn=978-1-4725-4187-1|passage=A dictionary, as an art and craft of '''lexicography''', has always been closely associated with the notion of pedagogy.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable|linguistics}} The [[scholarly]] [[discipline#Noun|discipline]] of [[analyse|analysing]] and [[describe|describing]] the [[semantic]], [[syntagmatic]] and [[paradigmatic]] [[relationship]]s within the [[lexicon]] ([[vocabulary]]) of a [[language]] and [[develop]]ing [[theory|theories]] of dictionary [[component]]s and [[structure#Noun|structures]] [[link#Verb|linking]] the [[data]] in dictionaries.
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Moses Stuart|authorlink=Moses Stuart|chapter=Changes of Consonants|title=A Grammar of the Hebrew Language|edition=3rd|location=Andover, Mass.|publisher=Flagg & Gould|year=1828|section=part II (Changes and Peculiarities of Consonants and Verbs), ¬ß&nbsp;105|page=51|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=zyItAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA51|oclc=1036194|passage=But changes of this nature belong to '''''lexicography''''', as they do not affect the grammatical forms of words.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Geo. Benedict Winer [''i.e.'', {{w|Georg Benedikt Winer}}]|chapter=¬ß&nbsp;4. Grammatical Character of the N.T. Diction.|translators=J. H Agnew and O. G. Ebbeke|title=A Grammar of the Idioms of the Greek Language of the New Testament|location=Philadelphia, Pa.|publisher=Herman Hooker,{{nb...|corner of Chesnut and 5th Street.}}|year=1840|section=part I|page=37|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=c7JNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA37|oclc=982205048|passage=What the history of language in general teaches, that in course of time, there is less change in form than signification, in grammar than '''lexicography''', is true of the Greek.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Wilhelm Freund|authorlink=Wilhelm Freund|title=Article IV. Principles of Latin Lexicography.|translator=[[w:Theodore Dwight Woolsey|T[heodore] D[wight] Woolsey]]|editors=[[w:Bela Bates Edwards|B[ela] B[ates] Edwards]] and [[w:Edwards Amasa Park|E[dwards] A[masa] Park]]|journal=[[w:Bibliotheca Sacra|Bibliotheca Sacra and Theological Review]]|location=New York, N.Y.; London|publisher=[[w:Wiley (publisher)|Wiley & Putnam]]; Andover, Mass.: Allen, Morrill and Wardwell|month=February|year=1845|volume=II|issue=V|section=section I (Of the Idea and Elements of Latin Lexicography), ¬ß&nbsp;1|page=80|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=9uEWAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA80|oclc=6052689|passage=If '''Lexicography''' in general is that science whose task it is to set forth the nature of every single word of a language through all the periods of its existence, it is the task of Latin '''lexicography''' in particular to set forth the nature of every single word of the Latin language, as it makes itself known in all the periods of the existence of that language; or more succinctly expressed, it is the object of Latin '''lexicography''' to give the history of every single word of the Latin language.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=C. J. Ball|title=A Study in Biblical Philology|journal=Proceedings of the Society of Biblical Arch√¶ology|location=London|publisher={{w|Society of Biblical Archaeology}}|date=13 December 1911|volume=XXXIII|issue=CCXLIX|page=13|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=qQsaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA13|oclc=1113492364|passage=[T]he philologist may well refuse to accept a body of triliteral roots, developed on a highly artificial and uniform plan, as the ultimate fact in Semitic '''lexicography'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Howard Jackson|chapter=Criticising Dictionaries|title=Lexicography: An Introduction|location=London; New York, N.Y.|publisher={{w|Routledge}}|year=2002|page=173|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=iQZK1NvRSMAC&pg=PA173|isbn=978-0-415-23172-5|passage=Academic '''lexicography''', or 'metalexicography', as pursued in university departments of English or Linguistics, is concerned not primarily with the compiling of dictionaries&nbsp;‚Äì though academics may be involved in this, as consultants, for example&nbsp;‚Äì but with researching and teaching about the whole business of making dictionaries: their history, their typology, their structures, their users, and so on [...].}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A dictionary, a [[lexicon]], a [[wordbook]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|author={{w|Joseph Story}}, Associate Judge of the [[w:Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]]|author2=William P. Mason, reporter|title=United States ''vs.'' an Open Boat and Lading|journal=Reports of Cases Argued and Determined in the Circuit Court of the United States, for the First Circuit|location=Boston, Mass.|publisher=Hilliard, Gray, Little, and Wilkins|month=October|year=1828|year_published=1831|volume=V|page=134|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=zyE8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA134|oclc=1013340480|passage=There can be no doubt, that in a general sense a ''boat'' is a ''vessel'', for it is "a vehicle in which men or goods are carried on the water," which is one of the definitions of a ''vessel'' given in our '''lexicographies'''; [...]}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=A Bag of Wind|magazine=[[w:Putnam's Magazine|Putnam‚Äôs Monthly. A Magazine of Literature, Science, and Art]]|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=Dix & Edwards,{{nb...|10 Park Place.}}; London: [[w:Sampson Low|Sampson Low, Son & Co.]]|month=March|year=1855|volume=V|issue=XXVII|page=251|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nlw3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA251|column=1|oclc=221113463|passage="Air put in motion" is the brief description of the wind in '''lexicographies'''; but what a contrast in quality according to its direction; [...]}}
