==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|frm|dialecte}}, from {{der|en|la|dialectos}}, {{m|la|dialectus}}, from {{der|en|grc|Œ¥ŒπŒ¨ŒªŒµŒ∫œÑŒøœÇ||conversation, the language of a country or a place or a nation, the local idiom which derives from a dominant language}}, from {{m|grc|Œ¥ŒπŒ±ŒªŒ≠Œ≥ŒøŒºŒ±Œπ||I participate in a dialogue}}, from {{m|grc|Œ¥ŒπŒ¨||inter, through}} + {{m|grc|ŒªŒ≠Œ≥œâ||I speak}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/Ààda…™.…ôÀål…õkt/}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-dialect.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|linguistics}} A [[variety]] of a [[language]] that is characteristic of a particular [[area]], [[community]]{{,}} or [[social group]], differing from other varieties of the same language in relatively minor ways as regards [[grammar]], [[phonology]], and [[lexicon]].
#: {{hypo|en|sociolect|ethnolect|regiolect|geolect}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1988|author=Andrew Radford|title=Transformational Grammar: A First Course|location=Cambridge, UK|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=139|passage=And in addition, many '''dialects''' of English make no morphological distinction between Adjectives and Adverbs, and thus use Adjectives in contexts where the standard language requires ''-ly'' Adverbs}}
# {{lb|en|pejorative}} Language that is perceived as substandard or wrong.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1975|title=Linguistic Perspectives on Black English|author=H. Carl|page=219|passage=Well, those children don't speak '''dialect''', not in this school. Maybe in the public schools, but not here.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1994|author=H. Nigel Thomas|title=Spirits in the Dark|publisher=Heinemann|page=11|passage={{...}} on the second day, Miss Anderson gave the school a lecture on why it was wrong to speak '''dialect'''. She had ended by saying "Respectable people don't speak '''dialect'''."}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1967|author=Roger W. Shuy|title=Discovering American Dialects|publisher=National Council of Teachers of English|page=1|passage=Many even deny it and say something like this: "No, we don't speak a '''dialect''' around here.}}
# {{lb|en|colloquial}} A language existing only in an oral or non-standardized form, especially a language spoken in a developing country or an isolated region.
#: {{syn|en|vernacular}}
# {{lb|en|colloquial}} A [[lect]] (often a {{l|en|regional}} or {{l|en|minority}} language) as part of a group or family of languages, especially if they are viewed as a single language, or if contrasted with a [[standardized]] [[idiom]] that is considered the 'true' form of the language (for example, [[Cantonese]] as contrasted with [[Mandarin]] [[Chinese]], or [[Bavarian]] as contrasted with [[Standard German]]).
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1995 |title=The German Language in a Changing Europe  |author= Michael Clyne & Michael G. Clyne |page=117 |ISBN=0521499704 |passage=The question could be put: 'Is there anything inherent in a '''dialect''' which gives it a negative stigma or is it that the status of the majority of the speakers is transferred to the '''dialect'''?' ‚Äî something that occurs in many regions in different countries. }}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010|title=Variation and Change: Pragmatic perspectives  |author=Mirjam Fried, Jan-Ola √ñstman, & Jef Verschueren  |page= 61|ISBN=9027289174 |passage=Bloomfield, for example, noted that ‚Äúlocal '''dialects''' are spoken by the peasants and the poorest people of the towns‚Äù (1933: 50) though he also thought that the lower middle class spoke 'sub-standard' speech.  }}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2014 |title=Rustic Speech and Folk-Lore |author=Elizabeth Mary Wright  |page= |ISBN= |passage=Among common errors still persisting in the minds of educated people, one error which dies very hard is the theory that a '''dialect''' is an arbitrary distortion of the mother tongue, a wilful mispronunciation of the sounds, and disregard of the syntax of a standard language.}}
#: {{syn|en|vernacular|patois|q2=often derogatory}}
# {{lb|en|computing|programming}} A [[variant]] of a non-[[standardize]]d [[programming language]].
#: {{ux|en|Home computers in the 1980s had many incompatible '''dialects''' of BASIC.}}
# {{lb|en|ornithology}} A variant form of the [[vocalizations]] of a bird species restricted to a certain area or population.
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1896|author=Alfred Newton|authorlink=Alfred Newton|title=A Dictionary of Birds|page=893|passage=A curious question, which has as yet attracted but little attention, is whether the notes of the same species of Bird are in all countries alike. From my own observation I am inclined to think that they are not, and that there exist "'''dialects'''," so to speak, of the song.}}

====Usage notes====
* In some linguistic traditions, the term "dialect" is restricted to [[nonstandard]] [[lect]]s. In scholarly English usage, it refers to both standardized and [[vernacular]] forms of language.<ref>{{Cite book|last=McGregor|first=William|title=Linguistics: An Introduction|publisher=A&C Black|year=2009|isbn=9781847063670|page=160}}</ref>
* The difference between a language and a dialect is not always clear, and often has more to do with political boundaries than with linguistic differences. It is generally considered that people who speak different dialects of the same language can understand each other, while people who speak different languages cannot, however, in some cases, people who speak different dialects of the same language are mutually unintelligible. Compare '''[[species]]''' in the biological sense.

