# {{lb|en|transitive}} To convert a word to a noun.
#* '''1974''', [https://books.google.ca/books?id=9ny6AAAAIAAJ The Modern Schoolman], page 144:
#*: What is not clear is how the '''nouning''' of verbs supports Simon's assumed correspondence between mechanical designing and intentional human responses. Is it the very '''nouning''' of verbs which indicates that the above correspondence exists?
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1992|author=Lewis Acrelius Froman|title=Language and Power: Books III, IV, and V|passage=For example, that females are different from but equal to males is oxymoronic by virtue of the '''nouned''' status of female and male as kinds of persons.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2000|author=Andrew J. DuBrin|title=The complete idiot's guide to leadership|passage=However, too much '''nouning''' makes you sound bureaucratic, immature, and verbally challenged. Top executives convert far fewer nouns into verbs than do workers at lower levels.}}

