==English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|swop}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/sw…íp/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-swap.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-M√©lange a trois-swap.wav |Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|en|…íp}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|swappen|t=to swap}}, originally meaning "to hurl" or "to strike", the word alludes to striking hands together when making an exchange; probably from {{inh|en|ang|*swappian}}, a secondary form of {{inh|en|ang|swƒÅpan||to swoop}}. Cognate with {{cog|de|schwappen||to swap}}. Compare also {{noncog|enm|swippen|t=to strike, hit}}, from {{noncog|ang|swipian|t=to scourge, strike, beat, lash}}, {{noncog|non|svipa|t=to swoop, flash, whip, look after, look around}}. More at {{m|en|swipe}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[exchange#Verb|exchange]] or [[give]] (something) in an exchange (for something else).
#: {{synonyms|en|exchange|switch|trade}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Religion in the workplace|page=98|author=Michael Wolf|coauthors=Bruce Friedman, Daniel Sutherland|year=1998|passage=In an effort to provide more permanent accommodations, employers may offer employees the opportunity either to '''swap''' jobs with a colleague or to transfer to a new position.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=A Season of Fire and Ice|author=Lloyd Zimpel|year=2007|passage=Chief watched these goings-on without pleasure, and waved them off in disgust when the smarmiest of the two suggested he might wish to '''swap''' that elk's tooth for this jug of fine rye whiskey.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=The Oil Kings: How the U.S., Iran, and Saudi Arabia Changed the Balance of Power in the Middle East|page=253|author=Andrew Scott Cooper|year=2011|passage=The Shah wanted to '''swap''' oil for more arms.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[hit#Verb|hit]], to [[strike#Verb|strike]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1954|author=Edward Eager|title=Half Magic|passage=And he whipped ''his'' sword out of ''its'' scabbard, and '''swapped''' off the pudding from the black knight's nose. Unfortunately (for him) he '''swapped''' off a good bit of the nose, too.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[beat#Verb|beat]] the [[air#Noun|air]], or [[ply#Verb|ply]] the [[wing#Noun|wings]], with a [[sweeping#Adjective|sweeping]] [[motion]] or [[noise]]; to [[flap#Verb|flap]].
# {{lb|en|intransitive|obsolete}} To [[descend]] or [[fall#Verb|fall]]; to [[rush#Verb|rush]] [[hastily]] or [[violently]].
<!--this sense also found in Charles Richardson's "New Dictionary of the English Language" (1836-7)-->

=====Synonyms=====
* {{sense|exchange or give (something) in exchange for}} {{l|en|interchange}}, {{l|en|switch}}; See also [[Thesaurus:switch]]
* {{sense|hit, strike}} {{l|en|bang}}, {{l|en|knock}}, {{l|en|tap}}; See also [[Thesaurus:hit]]
* {{sense|beat the air}} {{l|en|flap}}
* {{sense|rush hastily}} {{l|en|fly}}, {{l|en|speed}}, {{l|en|zoom}}; See also [[Thesaurus:rush]]

=====Hyponyms=====
