==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|trade||path, course of conduct}}, introduced into English by Hanseatic merchants, from {{der|en|gml|trade||track, course}}, from {{der|en|osx|trada||spoor, track}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*trad≈ç||track, way}}, and cognate with {{cog|ang|tredan||to tread}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en|En-uk-trade.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
* {{IPA|en|/t…πe…™d/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-trade.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|e…™d}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable}} Buying and selling of goods and services on a [[market]].
#: {{syn|en|commerce}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A particular instance of [[buy]]ing or [[sell]]ing.
#: {{ux|en|I did no '''trades''' with them once the rumors started.}}
#: {{syn|en|deal|barter}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} An instance of [[barter]]ing items in [[exchange]] for one another.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1989|author={{w|Bruce Pandolfini}}|title=Chess Openings: Traps and Zaps|isbn=0671656902|section=Glossary|page=225|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=pocVITTr8tMC&pg=PA225&dq=trade|passage=EXCHANGE ‚Äî A '''trade''' or swap of no material profit to either side.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2009|author=Elliott Kalb and Mark Weinstein|title=The 30 Greatest Sports Conspiracy Theories of All Time|isbn=9781602396784|page=60|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=nQd8MHuaXysC&pg=PA60&dq=trade|passage=When Golden State matched the Knicks' offer sheet, the Warriors and Knicks worked out a '''trade''' that sent King to New York for Richardson.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} Those who [[perform]] a particular kind of [[skilled]] work.
#: {{ux|en|The skilled '''trades''' were the first to organize modern labor unions.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author={{w|Edwin Black}}| title=Internal Combustion| chapter=2| url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL4103950W| passage=But through the oligopoly, charcoal fuel proliferated throughout London's '''trades''' and industries.&nbsp; By the 1200s, brewers and bakers, tilemakers, glassblowers, pottery producers, and a range of other craftsmen all became hour-to-hour consumers of charcoal.}}
#: {{syn|en|business}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} Those engaged in an industry or group of related industries.
#: {{ux|en|It is not a retail showroom. It is only for the '''trade'''.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} The skilled practice of a practical [[occupation]].
#* '''1969''', Paul Simon, Simon & Garfunkel, ‚ÄúThe Boxer‚Äù, ''Bridge over Troubled Water'', Columbia Records:
#*: In the clearing stands a boxer and a fighter by his '''trade'''
#: {{ux|en|He learned his '''trade''' as an [[apprentice]].}}
#: {{syn|en|craft}}
# {{lb|en|countable|or|uncountable}} An [[occupation]] in the [[secondary sector]], as opposed to an [[agricultural]], [[professional]] or [[military]] one.
#: {{ux|en|After failing his entrance exams, he decided to go into a '''trade'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|Most veterans went into '''trade''' when the war ended.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2007|author=Michael Lynch| title=The Oxford Companion to Scottish History| publisher=Oxford University Press| location=USA| isbn=9780199234820| page=228| passage=Subsequently some Scottish troops settled, took up '''trade''' as weavers, tailors, or mariners, and married Dutch women.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|author=Liberty Carrington|title=Wide Eyes Closed|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=9781477293898|page=92|passage=Getting a job in your major is no breeze: Remember we made fun of those who took up a '''trade'''}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable|UK}} The [[business]] given to a [[commercial]] [[establishment]] by its customers.
#: {{ux|en|Even before noon there was considerable '''trade'''.}}
#: {{syn|en|patronage}}
# {{lb|en|mostly|in the plural}} [[steady|Steady]] [[wind]]s blowing from east to west above and below the [[equator]].
#: {{ux|en|They rode the '''trades''' going west.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|1826|James Horsburgh|India Directory, Or Directions for Sailing to and from the East Indies, China, New Holland, Cape of Good Hope, Brazil and the Interjacent Ports||28|Calms and variable winds, are also experienced during every month of the year, in the space between the '''trades''';{{...}} the vicinity of the north-east '''trade''' seems most liable to them.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ctJYAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA28|origyear=1816}}
# {{lb|en|only as plural}} A publication intended for participants in an industry or related group of industries.
#: {{ux|en|Rumors about layoffs are all over the '''trades'''.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable|gay slang}} A [[masculine]] man available for [[casual sex]] with men, often for pay. {{non-gloss definition|(Compare ''[[rough trade]]''.)}}
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|year=1950|author={{w|W. H. Auden}}|title=A Playboy of the Western World: St. Oscar, The Homintern Martyr|journal={{w|Partisan Review}}|url=http://archives.bu.edu/collections/partisan-review/search/detail?id=284002|page=391-2|text=In a homosexual of this kind‚Äîcorresponding to the test of eccentric behavior in the drawing-room‚Äîone usually finds a preference for "'''trade'''," i.e., sexually normal males, because, if another homosexual yields to him, he is only one of a class, but if he can believe that an exception is being made in his case, it seems a proof that he is being accepted for himself alone.}}
#: {{ux|en|Josh picked up some '''trade''' last night.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete|uncountable}} Instruments of any occupation.
#* {{quote-book|en|1697|{{w|John Dryden}}|The works of Virgil containing his Pastorals, Georgics and Aeneis||112|His House and household Gods! his '''trade''' of War, / His Bow and Quiver; and his trusty Cur.|chapter=The Third Book of the Georgics|url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A65112.0001.001/1:18.3?rgn=div2;view=fulltext}}
# {{lb|en|mining}} Refuse or rubbish from a mine.
