==English==
{{was wotd|2009|August|17}}

===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|la|[[quid]] [[pr≈ç]] [[qu≈ç]]|lit=something for something}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/Àåkw…™d.p…π…ô äÀàkw…ô ä/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/Àåkw…™d.p…πo äÀàkwo ä/}}
* {{audio|en|en-au-quid pro quo.ogg|Audio (AU)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|quae pro quibus|quid pro quibus|s}}

# Something which is understood as something else; an [[equivocation]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1844|by={{w|Arthur Schopenhauer}}|type=translation|author=[[s:Author:Richard Burdon Haldane|Richard Burdon Haldane]]|title=[[s:The World as Will and Representation/First Book|''The World as Will and Representation'', 2nd edition, first book]]|section=13|passage=The misunderstanding of the word or the '''quid pro quo''' is the unintentional pun, and is related to it exactly as folly is to wit.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1912|by={{w|Fyodor Dostoevsky}}|type=translation|author=[[s:Constance Garnett|Constance Garnett]]|title=[[s:The Brothers Karamazov/Book V/Chapter 5|The Brothers Karamazov]]|section=part II, book V, chapter 5|passage=&ldquo;Is it simply a wild fantasy, or a mistake on the part of the old man &mdash; some impossible '''quid pro quo'''?&rdquo;}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1982|title=Esthetics of Music|author=Carl Dahlhaus|page=52|passage=His argument was formulated, not without reason, as a paradox, a '''quid pro quo''' of opposing concepts: form is declared to be content, thus its own opposite.}}
# {{lb|en|historical}} Substitution of one drug for another.
#* {{quote-book|en|title={{w|Anatomy of Melancholy}}|author={{w|Robert Burton}}|year=1621-51|passage=a knave Apothecary that administers the Physick, and makes the medicine, may doe infinite harme, by his old obsolete doses, adulterine druggs, bad mixtures, '''''quid pro quo''''', etc.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Outlines of the History of Medicine and the Medical Profession|author=Johann Hermann Baas, Henry Ebenezer Handerson|year=1889|page=263|passage=Nicholas [Praepositus] was also the author of a "'''Quid pro Quo'''", that is an alphabetically arranged catalogue of equivalent drugs, capable of replacing each other, when for any reason one or the other drug was wanting}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=Druggists Circular|volume=61|page=188|year=1917|title=History of Substitutes and Substitution|author=Otto Raubenheimer|passage=Was it not Claudius Galenus (130-200 A. D.), the great Roman physician-pharmacist, who was about the very first to prepare a lengthy list of drugs, '''quid pro quo''', a list which remained in use until about the sixteenth century?}}
# Something which is offered or asked for in exchange for something else.
#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The Parliamentary History of England from the Earliest Period to the Year 1803|volume=35|year=1819|page=1129|passage=To him I offered a '''quid pro quo'''; and meant to give nothing without getting a full equivalent.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Authority and Upheaval in Leipzig, 1910-1920|year=2001|page=148|passage=Whie Demanding Great sacrifices from the workforce, Germany's rulers had proved unable by autumn 1916 to offer a '''quid pro quo''' in the form of a military victory, more democracy, or even a modest redistribution of income.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2007|author=Associated Press|title=Iran to release 15 British sailors|journal=China Daily|passage=Britain, which said its crew was in Iraqi waters when seized, insists it never offered a '''quid pro quo''', either, instead relying on quiet diplomacy.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=Mar 24, 2012|journal=Forbes|title=The World Bank Is Broken: Can The New President Fix It?|author=Steve Denning|passage=the US recently supported the European candidate for the IMF and may receive a '''quid pro quo'''}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=What Mercedes buy-out of Brawn could mean|journal=BBC Sport|author=Andrew Benson|date=16 November 2009|passage=McLaren did not want Mercedes to buy Brawn so when the German company insisted, they demanded a '''quid pro quo''' that, as far as McLaren are concerned, contains all the positives of a Mercedes involvement but none of the negatives.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2014|title=Nice Girls Don't Get the Corner Office|author=Lois P. Frankel|passage=People don't like to talk about it, but inherent to every relationship there's a '''quid pro quo'''‚Äî something that's exchanged in return for something else. The '''quid pro quo''' can be obvious, such as ''I give you a salary and in return I expect you to do a good job'', or more subtly, ''I give you a recommendation and in turn expect you'll help me get my expense check processed faster''. It's an unspoken system of bartering that goes on in relationships. Women aren't very good at capitalizing on the '''quid pro quo'''. Instead, they give away favors and expect little or nothing in return.}}
# A usually non-monetary exchange transaction, or series or process of exchange transactions.
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Corporate Welfare Policy and the Welfare State|author=Davita Silfen Glasberg, Daniel L. Skidmore|page=138|year=1997|passage=More importantly, the Chrysler bailout produced a '''quid pro quo''' wherein Congress agreed to pass bank deregulation legislation if banks agreed to convert substantial amounts of Chrysler's debt to equity.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2004|title=The Priest and the Great King: Temple-palace Relations in the Persian Empire|author=Lisbeth S. Fried|page=74|passage=The apparent exception at the Temple of Neith at Sais is likely due to an agreement, a '''quid pro quo''', made with Udjahorresnet, not to a failure to enact the command immediately.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|title=Administration of Government Contracts|author=John Cibinic, Jr., Ralph C. Nash, James F. Nagle|page=84|passage=The requisite intent is proved by showing a '''quid pro quo'''‚Äîan expectation of a favorable official act in return for the bribe.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=Forbes|date=Dec 14, 2011|title=Business Networking That Works ... It's Called '''Quid Pro Quo'''|author=Susan T. Spencer|passage=I call it '''quid pro quo''' while other authors have described it as ‚Äúthe art of reciprocity.‚Äù}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|title=Tax Planning and Compliance for Tax-Exempt Organizations|author=Jody Blazek|passage=Neither the envelope nor the entry form indicated whether a donation was enclosed. Because there was no obligation to pay to enter the sweepstakes, payments voluntarily sent were fully deductible. No '''quid pro quo''' occurred.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=July 13, 2016|title=SCOTUS ''Quid Pro Quo'' Analysis in McDonnell May Broadly Affect Bribery & Insider Trading Prosecutions|journal=Forbes|author=Robert Anello|passage=All are based on the concept of '''''quid pro quo''''', or ‚Äúthis for that‚Äù ‚Äì the exchange of one thing for another.&nbsp;{{...}}&nbsp;In McDonnell, the government alleged a '''''quid pro quo''''' sale of ‚Äúofficial action‚Äù ‚Äì payments (the ''quid'') made to McDonnell, the former governor of Virginia, in return for a promise or undertaking by McDonnell to perform an official action (the ''quo''). The Court‚Äôs decision focused on the ''quo'' side of the equation ‚Äì a side that does not often receive much scrutiny ‚Äì analyzing the contours of whether the actions taken by McDonnell constituted illegal ‚Äúofficial actions.‚Äù}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=69 News|date=March 4, 2019|title=Phillipsburg council calls for new investigation of alleged '''quid pro quo'''|passage=Council says the mayor and a former councilman may have engaged in a "'''quid pro quo'''."&nbsp;/ {{...}}&nbsp;/ Council says, according to a handwritten note, Fey offered to support a pay raise for Mayor Ellis if Ellis would support a raise or a job appointment for Fey's wife, Gina.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2018|title=Quid Pro Quo|author=Vicki Grant|passage=All I'm asking for is a little '''quid pro quo'''. You know‚Äîyou scratch my back, I'll scratch yours.}}
## An equal or fair transaction or series of process of exchange transactions; [[tit for tat]].
##* {{quote-book|en|year=1837|title=The Congressional Globe|author=United States. Congress|page=1977|passage=Mr. P. did not consider that branch, strictly and technically speaking, public revenue; at least it did not arise from taxation, because those persons who had paid this money had received a full equivalent for the same; there was a '''quid pro quo''' on both sides; and this was not taxation, it was a sale; the parties therefore from whom this money was derived had not been taxed.}}
<!--##* {{quote-book|en|year=1895|author=Uchimura Kanzo|title=[[s:The Diary of a Japanese Convert|The Diary of a Japanese Convert]]|chapter=1|passage=No less weightier was to be the youth's consideration for his master, who was to him no mere school teacher or college professor on '''quid pro quo''' principle, but a veritable didaskalos, in whom he could and must completely confide the care of his body and soul.}}-->
##* {{quote-book|en|year=1988|title=Industrial R&D and U.S. Technological Leadership|passage=What we should do, however, is insist that there be a '''quid pro quo''' ‚Äî an equal exchange.}}
##* {{quote-book|en|title=Corruption in America|author=Zephyr Teachout|year=2014|page=239|passage=Most of those cases were about witness immunity deals (was there a quid pro quo?) or the meaning of '''quid pro quo''' in the classic ‚Äúequality of exchange‚Äù sense.}}
##* {{quote-journal|en|title=Quid Pro Quo Diplomacy in US-Myanmar Relations|journal=Foreign Policy Journal|author=Nehginpao Kipgen|date=May 21, 2013|passage=US-Myanmar relations in the past few years have been largely based on a '''quid pro quo''' or tit for tat strategy. Some analysts also call it action for action or give and take strategy.}}
# {{lb|en|legal}} [[sexual harassment|Sexual harassment]] in which a person in a workplace implicitly or explicitly [[require]]s  sexual favours in exchange for something.
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Promoting Legal and Ethical Awareness|author=Ronald W. Scott|year=2008|page=140|passage=A '''quid pro quo''' complaint typically is lodged by an employee who has been denied opportunities because he or she refused a perpetrator's sexual advances or by an employee who has been denied opportunities because another employee obtained those opportunities by submitting to a perpetrator's sexual advances.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2009|title=Inventing Equal Opportunity|author=Frank Dobbin|passage=As for a legal remedy to the problem of harassment, the Court found that a proper, well-advertised grievance procedure could be used in a defense where sexual comments and horseplay created a ‚Äúhostile environment,‚Äù but not in the '''quid pro quo''' cases that feminist Catharine MacKinnon had dubbed "put out or get out."}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2018|title=A Practical Guide to Equal Employment Opportunity|author=Walter B. Connolly, Jr., Michael J. Connolly, Joshua Feinstein|page=161|passage=American courts have recognized two forms of sexual harassment. In the first, '''quid pro quo''' cases, the violation occurs when an employer or supervisor conditions an employment benefit on the employee's providing sexual favors.}}

