==English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|fah}}

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|la|famuli}}, from the first word of the fourth line of ''[[w:Ut queant laxis|Ut queant laxis]]'', the medieval hymn which [[solf√®ge]] was based on because its lines started on each note of the scale successively.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/f…ë/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-fa.wav|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|en|…ëÀê}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|music}} A syllable used in [[solf√®ge]] to represent the fourth note of a [[major scale]].
#* {{RQ:Fielding Tom Jones|IV|X|Containing the Arrival of an ''Irish'' Gentleman, with very extraordinary Adventures which ensued at the Inn|pages=11‚Äì12|pageref=11|passage=And now Mrs. ''Waters'' (for we mu≈øt confe≈øs ≈øhe was in the ≈øame Bed) being, I ≈øuppo≈øe, awakened from her Sleep, and ≈øeeing two Men fighting in her Bed-chamber, began to ≈øcream in the mo≈øt violent Manner, crying out Murder! Robbery! and more frequently Rape! which la≈øt, ≈øome, perhaps, may wonder ≈øhe ≈øhould mention, who do not con≈øider that the≈øe Words of Exclamation are u≈øed by Ladies in a Fright, as '''Fa''', la, la, ra, da, ''&c.'' are in Mu≈øic, only as the Vehicles of Sound, and without any fixed Ideas.}}

