==English==

===Alternative forms===
*{{l|en|fabian}}

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|la|Fabianus||belonging to Fabius}}, possibly derived from {{m|la|faba||bean}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/Ààfe…™bi.…ôn/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-Fabian.wav|Audio (RP)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Pertaining to or reminiscent of Roman general {{w|Fabius Maximus}}, whose tactics against Hannibal during the Second Punic War famously consisted of delaying or avoiding combat, focusing instead on weakening the enemy by cutting off supply lines.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1988|author=James McPherson|title=Battle Cry of Freedom|publisher=Oxford|year_published=2004|page=745|passage=Hood complained behind his commander's back to Richmond of Johnston's '''Fabian''' strategy.}}
# Advocating that social reforms be reached through a series of gradual and moderate stages rather than sudden [[revolution]]; specifically, relating to the Fabian Society, a British socialist society advocating [[reformist]] [[socialism]].
# {{lb|en|by extension}} [[cautious]]; [[dilatory]]; [[avoiding]] a [[decisive]] contest.

====Translations====
{{trans-top|all senses}}
* German: {{t+|de|fabisch}}
{{trans-mid}}
* Italian: {{t|it|fabiano}}
{{trans-bottom}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A Fabian [[socialist]], a [[gradualist]] socialist; a member of the Fabian Society.
#: {{syn|en|gradualist|reformist|social democrat}}

====Related terms====
* {{l|en|Fabianism}}

===Proper noun===
{{en-proper noun}}

# {{given name|en|male|from=Latin}} borne by an early pope. Rare in English.

