===Proper noun===
{{sv-proper noun|c}}

# {{given name|sv|male}}

==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*b ∞eh‚ÇÇ-|id=speak}}
From {{inh|en|enm|-}}, borrowed from {{bor|en|fro|fable}}, from {{der|en|la|fƒÅbula}}, from {{m|la|for|fƒÅrƒ´|to speak, say}} + {{m|la|-bula||instrumental suffix}}. See {{m|en|ban}}, and compare {{m|en|fabulous}}, {{m|en|fame}}. {{doublet|en|fabula}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|fƒÅ‚Ä≤b…ôl}}, {{IPA|en|/Ààfe…™b…ôl/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-fable.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|e…™b…ôl}}
* {{hyphenation|en|fa|ble}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[fictitious]] [[narrative]] intended to [[enforce]] some useful [[truth]] or [[precept]], usually with [[animals]], etc. as [[characters]]; an [[apologue]]. Prototypically, [[w:Aesop's Fables|Aesop's Fables]].
#: {{syn|en|morality play}}
# Any story told to excite wonder; common talk; the [[theme]] of talk.
#* {{RQ:KJV|1 Timothy|4|7}}
#*: Old wives' '''fables'''.
#* {{quote-book|en|1842|{{w|Alfred Tennyson, 1st Baron Tennyson|Alfred Tennyson}}|The Gardener's Daughter; or, The Pictures|passage={{...}}we grew / The '''fable''' of the city where we dwelt.}}
#: {{syn|en|legend}}
# [[fiction|Fiction]]; [[untruth]]; falsehood.
#* {{quote-book|en|1711|{{w|Joseph Addison}}|The Spectator|volume=the fourth|section=no. 264|passage=I say it wou'd look like a '''fable''' to report that this gentleman gives away all which is the overplus of a great fortune by secret methods, to other men.}}
# The plot, story, or connected series of events forming the subject of an epic or dramatic poem.
#* {{quote-book|en|1695|{{w|John Dryden}}|A Parallel betwixt Painting and Poetry|passage=For the moral (as Bossu observes,) is the first business of the poet, as being the groundwork of his instruction. This being formed, he contrives such a design, or '''fable''', as may be most suitable to the moral;}}

====Derived terms====
* {{l|en|personal fable}}
* {{l|en|fabulist}}

