==English==

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|a-|t=up, out, away}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ƒÅ-}}, originally {{m|ang|*ar-}}, {{m|ang|*or-}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*uz-|t=out-}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*uds-|t=up, out}}. Cognate with {{cog|osx|ƒÅ-}}, {{cog|de|er-}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/…ô/}}

====Prefix====
{{en-prefix}}

# {{lb|en|no longer productive}} {{non-gloss definition|Forming verbs with the sense ''away'', ''up'', ''on'', ''out''.}}
#: '''''a'''rise, '''a'''wait''
# {{lb|en|no longer productive}} {{non-gloss definition|Forming verbs with the sense of intensified action.}}
#: '''''a'''bide, '''a'''maze''

===Etymology 2===
* A [[proclitic]] form of preposition {{m|en|a}}; from {{inh|en|ang|an|t=on}}
* See [[a]] {{qualifier|preposition|on, to, in, etc.}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/…ô/}}

====Prefix====
{{en-prefix}}

# {{lb|en|rare|or|no longer productive}} [[in|In]], [[on]], [[at]]; used to show a state, condition, or manner.  Also passing into sense 2. {{defdate|First attested prior to 1150}}<ref name=SOED>Brown, Lesley (2003)</ref>
#: '''''a'''pace, '''a'''fire, '''a'''boil, '''a'''-bling''
# {{lb|en|no longer productive}} In, into.  Also passing into sense 5. {{defdate|First attested prior to 1150}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: '''''a'''sunder''
# In the direction of, or [[toward]]. {{defdate|First attested prior to 1150}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: '''''a'''stern, '''a'''beam''
# {{lb|en|archaic|dialectal}} At such a time. {{defdate|First attested prior to 1150}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''Come '''a'''-morning we are going hunting.''
# {{lb|en|archaic|dialectal}} In the act or process of.  Being conflated with the next definition, a- is used in some dialects to indicate any participle.  {{defdate|First attested prior to 1150}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* '''1777''', {{w|Thomas Arne}}, ''[[w:A-Hunting We Will Go|'''A'''-Hunting We Will Go]]''
#* '''1780''', ''[[w:The Twelve Days of Christmas (song)|The Twelve Days of Christmas]]'':<!-- Traditional lyrics, as per The Oxford Dictionary of Nursery Rhymes -->
#*: The twelfth day of Christmas,
#*: My true love sent to me
#*: Twelve lords '''a-'''leaping,
#*: ‚Ä¶
#*: Eight maids '''a-'''milking,
#*: Seven swans '''a-'''swimming,
#*: Six geese '''a'''-laying,
#* circa '''1850''', ''{{w|Here We Come A-wassailing}}/Here We Come A-caroling''
#*: Here we come '''a-'''wassailing
#*: Among the leaves so green;
#*: Here we come '''a-'''wand‚Äôring
#*: So fair to be seen.
#* '''1939''', {{w|Alfred Edward Housman}}, ''Additional Poems'', XIII, lines 6-7:
#*: Oh waste no words '''a-'''wooing
#*: The soft sleep to your bed;
#* '''1964''', {{w|Bob Dylan}}, {{w|The Times They Are a-Changin' (song)|"The Times They Are a-Changin'&nbsp;"}} (recorded 1963, released 1964):
#*: The order is rapidly fadin'
#*: And the first one now will later be last
#*: For the times they are '''a-'''changin'
#* circa '''1970''', bumper sticker:<ref>See ‚Äú[http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DontComeAKnockin Don‚Äôt Come A-Knockin‚Äô]‚Äù, ''TV Tropes'' for more examples and discussion.</ref>
#*: If the van‚Äôs '''a-'''rockin‚Äô, don‚Äôt come '''a-'''knockin‚Äô.

===Etymology 3===
{{senseid|en|ge|tag=p}}
From {{inh|en|enm|a-}}, a variant form of {{m|enm|y-}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ƒ°e-}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*ga-}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*·∏±√≥m|t=with}}.
{{senseid-close|tag=p}}

====Alternative forms====
* {{l|en|i-}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/…ô/}}

====Prefix====
{{en-prefix}}

# {{obsolete form of|en|y-}} {{lb|en|archaic|and|dialectal}} {{n-g|In dialect, it is sometimes conflated with sense 5 of the previous definition, and is used as a general indicator of a participle.}} {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350 (Middle English).}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: '''''a'''ware, '''a'''like''

===Etymology 4===
From {{der|en|xno|a-}}, from {{der|en|fro|e-}}, from {{der|en|la|ex-}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/…ô/}}

====Prefix====
{{en-prefix}}

# {{lb|en|no longer productive}} {{non-gloss definition|Forming words with the sense of ''wholly'', or ''utterly'' ''out''.}} {{defdate|First attested from around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: '''''a'''bash''

===Etymology 5===
From {{der|en|grc|·ºÄ-}} ({{m|grc|·ºÄŒΩ-}} immediately preceding a vowel).

====Pronunciation====
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/…ô/|/e…™/}}

====Prefix====
{{en-prefix}}

# {{senseid|en|not}} [[not|Not]], without, opposite of.
#: '''''a'''moral, '''a'''symmetry, '''a'''theism, '''a'''sexual, '''a'''cyclic, '''a'''typical''
#* '''1948''' (revised 1952), {{w|Robert Graves}}, ''The White Goddess'', Faber & Faber 1999, page 7:
#*: When invited to believe in the Chimaera, the horse-centaurs, or the winged horse Pegasus, all of them straightforward Pelasgian cult-symbols, a philosopher felt bound to reject them as '''a'''-zo√∂logical improbabilities [...].
#* '''2012''', Faramerz Dabhoiwala, ''The Origins of Sex'', Penguin 2013, page 191:
#*: If aroused outside the proper outlet of marriage, [female lust] could range out of control, turning its possessor into an '''a-'''feminine monster: that is what happened to fallen women.

=====Usage notes=====
* This prefix is referred to as [[alpha privative]].
* Used with stems that begin with consonants except sometimes ''h''. {{m|en|an-}} is synonymous and is used in front of words that start with vowels and sometimes ''h''.<ref name=Rand>Urdang, Laurence (1984) </ref> For example, {{m|en|anesthetic}} and {{m|en|analgesic}}.

